Today, the Ukrainian Parliament, in the course of its amendments to the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to repeal the article condemning opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko.
An amendment that would have led to the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected at the time of the second reading of the bill on the mitigation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider Timoshenko's appeal in December.
Timoshenko claims that the sentence is a political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process is also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, according to which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
It would require 226 votes.
