Nutrition of obese children: No breakfast or sausage for dinner
More than one third of the children between the ages of 9 and 13 were overweight; while 9 per cent of the children were overweight, 5 per cent were obese.
According to a recent study, obesity-prone children usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and patterns of human behavior to his or her healthy development.
For example, a sausage shows up on the tables of obese children almost twice as often as in families with children with normal weight.
More than 19 per cent of obese children ate fries for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity is no accident.
Moreover, the families of obese children do not engage in sports, but most of the families of modern school children - only 15 per cent of the children said that their parents found time to engage in sports at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last school year, with nearly 900 primary school students throughout Bohemia participating.
Obesity was not an accident for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company VšeoCenná zdravotní pojiáovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils from 4 to 8 grades have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and sufficient exercise are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half of those interviewed said they were eating five meals a day, according to breakfast, lunch, dinner, which is a prerequisite for proper nutrition," says one of the conclusions of the study.
No lunch and no sausage at night
Experts warn that even relative details such as regular family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 per cent of school children's families have breakfast together.
In most families, everyone has breakfast alone.
The worst discovery is that in every tenth family, people don't have breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis for a proper daily diet.
The study found that roasted food is more common in families with obese children.
Almost every one, regardless of his weight, drinks sweet, cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children regularly engage in sports, this figure falls more than half, to 15 per cent, when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to develop their own menu based on the proposed products and based on their own tastes and preferences.
“Food preferences for Czech children aged 12-15 years are far from ideal for healthy nutrition.”
Their favorite food includes large amounts of flour, meat, and sweet food.
"A particular concern is the high popularity of sweet cool drinks," says the final part of the study.
A small overhanged bird was defeated by pasta as the main dish of food.
However, children showed little interest in legumes, fish and vegetables.
Desire for a Healthy Life - Style
The study also showed that children are prepared to change their eating habits, provided that they are provided with relevant information.
“Many of the members of the monitoring group have shown a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they filled out the questionnaire after the lecture was completed - this is not an accident,” says the outcome of the project.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet, cool drinks, with more children choosing just water.
In addition, children were more likely to observe poultry and fish as the main food, limiting the number of sweets and pastries.
