IBM is entering the second century of its existence.
If someone wants to find a word that best expresses the IMB strategy, the closest one is likely to be "long-lived."
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is regarded as very modern, although it was founded over a hundred years ago.
The company's longitude was built by her first boss, Thomas J. Watson's senior dreamer.
He believed that many of the world’s problems could be solved easily if people wanted to think.
His "Duma" slogan thus became the image around which the life of the future giant unfolded (and also the name of its internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of a corporate culture that Watson had carefully built.
"To us in IBM, long-term thinking means a steady movement towards the future.
IBM survived and flourished for a hundred years because it remained faithful to its original values, although not afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, this has enabled us to transform technology, business and company.
In the second hundred years, we hope to achieve even more," says Samuel J. Palmizano, current director of the company on the occasion of the anniversary.
Complex system
