Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five State tourism agencies were able to work in the former Czechoslovakia: Şedok, Sportist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, the tourist agencies of the time were mainly selling tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was between 1962 and 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which placed considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel by himself, for example to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was needed; another individual trip was not possible.
At that time, travel agencies were offering to travel to the West, but they had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
The currency permit was necessary to travel to the West, and it was not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
Czechoslovakian currency was not freely convertible; without its authorization it was not possible to obtain money (west currency) for travel to the West.
The Czechs were most likely to spend their vacations at home, resulting in large numbers of cottages and summer homes, a habit that continues to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic has thus experienced a real revolution.
While pre-1989 leave in the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our journeys, last year Czechs held 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are no longer aware of is that until 1989, we were unable to visit freely the most popular Croatia today, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa in the neighbouring countries of Western Europe was abolished, which led to a huge wave of short trips mainly to Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovaks could not have been satisfied with their journeys to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income was not enough at the time for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring in its own food (conservation, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech kroner, and after decades our tourists can finally buy the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income have increased, leading to another important development around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter companies; compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap owing to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the late 1990s, the Czechs didn't need a visa to visit almost all the developed world countries except the United States, which made our journeys even easier.
The following significant event in the history of travel since the revolution took place in 2000: a great demand led to a historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have taken Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flights from the Czech Republic will be sent in twelve exotic directions.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important development of this period, which symbolizes our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the U.S. lifted the need for a visa for Czech tourists, and in this way, our country joined the most developed countries in the world forever.
For the first time in history, in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during overseas leave, including their expenditure at their destination.
