The walls have eyes: how researchers study you on Facebook.
Before becoming a new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Bering Braywick was a regular guy presenting his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braywick, who had confessed to the July massacre in Norway, which had claimed 77 lives, was present at his first public hearing.
Although Breavik may have been acting alone, he was far from alone on the Internet, spending a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, sharing with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, we just have to get on Facebook.
"We realized it's easy to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on the European cyber-populism of the British DeMOS Research Centre.
The personal data reserve on Facebook is so large, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the website's advertising tool to highlight the necessary demographic group with scientific accuracy -- what marketers have been doing for several years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then promoted them, but instead of showing them a new group or a diet product, the ad invited the user to conduct a survey that asked them about their level of education, their attitude towards violence and optimism about their own future.
With the help of Facebook Bartlett and his colleagues, over 10,000 participants from 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries were able to interview without even leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not as impressive: online parties to right-wing groups - most often young men who are not satisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with off-line activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who hide behind the monitor."
DEMOS is just one example of Facebook becoming a popular new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends, as expressed in the "Lakes", posts on the wall, and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three records per day, Facebook “super-actual information” is causing a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title of the site by 800 per cent over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be approached on the street with a notebook.
"Early, if you wanted to interview the people of the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have to join the party and they would never have accepted you," Bartlett says.
"Fastbook excludes all of this, you're addressing them directly."
Others say that the site could identify and study social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Whisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who were discussing their drinking exploits on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent on the matter.
Moreno suggests that students' peers, such as their hostels, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often renews his drinking status.
"You can't solve the problem without discovering it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christkis, co-author of Moreno and Director of the Center for Child Health, Conduct and Development at Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify children from the risk group who would not otherwise be found."
Facebook also constantly extracts various data about its users.
The site ' s data processing team has processed the status and day statistics of Valentine ' s Day, the turnout of voters in mid-2010, and the National Happiness Index (mostly using information that they only have access to - cyberbowder champions have long insisted that the site should make its extensive collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not, in exchange for the opportunity to play Skrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become involved in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict standards for off-line research, online data are publicly available.
"I don't think many users at least think that the researcher can observe their profile," says Neil Selwin, a sociologist from the London Knowledge Laboratory, "about a study he conducted in 2006 using publicly available Facebook students' pages.
"As they imagined, it was only between them and their friends."
Then the question of methodology arises.
Even off-line does not guarantee that the subject matter of the study is highly honest.
It is not possible to know on Facebook how much information in the profile and on the user's page is true.
"What you're saying on Facebook, and what you're doing outside Facebook, two completely different things," says Selwin.
That is why, despite his years of work in the field of technological research, Selwin believes that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools available for use.
"Nothing can replace entry into the real world and contact with real people," he said.
"It is assumed that social research is about social, and most social research is still about off-line."
