The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice (UB) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which has carried the so-called “digital television transition” from 2021 to 2015, since the eight votes required for its cancellation have not been obtained.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mess, believed that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his mandate by issuing a decree detailing the actions to be taken to move to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected because there was no qualified majority of the eight votes required by the court to express itself on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and it remains in force.
The draft declaration prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero proposed that the decree should be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right enshrined in the Act of the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofethel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margaret Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On the basis of this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and to support complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions referred to in it with regard to the transition to digital broadcasting.
It was also decided at the Ministerial Meeting to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the arguments of the draft in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules of action for which the public administration should prepare.
“I also do not believe that if this were to happen, it would affect regulatory autonomy”, and recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals, one of the most important changes in recent years, has resulted in better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of conversion to digital form, which included meeting public needs, which had not only a technical dimension, “because it covered economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These questions, he said, “require the work of the whole system of State economic governance includes a group of authorities which the Constitution unites into the State executive branch”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital broadcasting exercise and had done so with the help of the Executive, despite the existence of specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded, therefore, that the Government, in adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of the Congress, ensures that the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly are respected in the administrative field.
In Michokan, the possibility of counting "voice by voice" is being analysed.
According to the PRRA, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governorial Elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting “voting-by-voting” is real for the elections this year in Michoacan, where, according to the Provisional Results Programme (PARP), the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes, 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michoana Electoral Institute (IVC), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Saragosa, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Corps adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the State Constitution or Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, since the State Congress had approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their entry into force in this electoral process and Governor Lélèle Year-Radge had not included its publication within the time frame stipulated in the law in the Official Gazette of the State, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (CJJJ) ruled on the constitutional claim made by the local legislature and called the State representative's vote on constitutional reform “unvalid and illegal”, since he was not entitled “to permit or support them”.
In an interview on the possibility of “voting”, Maria de los Angeles Lianderal argued that, with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of the IWL, it would be possible to present a partial or complete count of votes to the local electoral body.
For example, partial counting of one or more ballot boxes may be done on the condition that: the results of the records do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting of documents in the urn or it is not in the Chair ' s possession; or where there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, the overall counting of votes in all ballot boxes may occur when there is a sign that the difference between the alleged candidate winner of the elections in question and those who obtained the second seat in the voting is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that, at the beginning of the session, there is a request from the representative of the party and/or the coalition that presented the second candidate.
The total counting will also be done if it is determined at the end of the normal calculation that the difference between the winner and the candidate who took the second place is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a petition from the political party whose candidate has taken the second place, in the event that the ballot boxes have been deleted, which have been counted in part.
It is worth noting that this is the case with elections in Morelia, where, according to the PRRA, only 0.16 per cent of the difference between the first and the second place, even with 129 votes, out of a total of 923 protocols.
