A new Italian Government will be established on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to introduce a new Government that will face a crisis that has placed the country on the verge of economic disaster.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present a new Government that will face a crisis that has placed Italy on the verge of economic disaster and damage to the entire eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace said that Monty, who had been appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President on Wednesday, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he could form a Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mainly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive branch takes its positions.
Monty said that he would present the results of his talks with the political parties to the President in his attempt to form a Government.
“I wish to reaffirm my full confidence in our country's ability to escape this difficult period”, said the former European Commissioner to reporters.
Monty did not explicitly say that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The art is now well framed," he said.
Monty has completed the process of government formation in less than three days, which is much less than usual, as Italy has been struggling with a political and financial crisis that has brought their debt to a critical level.
Under the leadership of the former European Commissioner of Monty, the administration must approve the rigid savings required by European leaders in order to regain confidence in Italy.
On the basis of pressure on Monty to hurry, unstable markets have established a 10-year increase in income from the BTP bonds of Italy over 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian Employers' Federation, told reporters after meeting with Monty, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this critical situation.
Monty ' s chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome," said Angelino Alphano, Secretary of the Centralist Right Party.
Support for the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have opposed the majority government, which is made up of technocrats, which Monty forms.
Parliamentary support
The new Government of Monty must have strong parliamentary support for reforms that are likely to be unpopular reforms of severe economies.
Any closure or suspension of these attempts could lead to a new and destructive attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks increased pressure to warn that Monty’s failure could be a disaster.
Monty started his consultations on Monday with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women ' s organizations.
He'll finish his meeting Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday of Napolitano, which allowed an extremely rapid transition to respond to the crisis.
After a short break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the value of Italy's debt had now reached a critical level in the face of uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would succeed.
Saving Italy with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros would be too much for modern financial advocates of the eurozone.
Monty said that his Government would exist prior to the next elections for 2013, despite widespread projections that politicians would only allow him time to undertake reforms before appointing new elections.
Monty said that he would like to include politicians in his office, but the main parties insist that it should be composed of only technical specialists, demonstrating their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources reported that mutual mistrust and opposition by the parties complicated the attempt to include political figures.
