UNAM asphalt can avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a UNAM chemical research scientist, has developed a polymer-moderated bitumen to produce a best quality mixture that is environmentally resistant and temperature resistant.
If the signals sent by the road surface were to be taken into consideration, it would be necessary to repair some 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the capital area of the Valley of Mexico City, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, researcher of the UNAM Chemical Department, and adds that if the construction and maintenance of asphalted road surfaces is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or reduced to zero.
In his lecture, the Technology View of the Holes read in the International Year of Chemistry reports that the Laboratory for which he is responsible is developing a polymer-moderated bitumen to produce a mixture with the characteristics close to bitumen but with the best resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather was extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus counteracting the formation of pits.
He explained that the bitumen, the most heavy part of oil, was a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some of the high molecular mass known as asphaltons, and others the low molecular mass known as boys, which together gave the road surface its characteristic viscosity.
The obsessive behavior of the bitumen is the fact that, at a high speed of about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it remains almost stable, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance to street asphalt is not constant, but changes over the course of the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineer.
He observed that the streets of Mexico City were mostly covered with a flexible coating made up of six layers of material, the last three of which included bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen, made up of small stones, dropped in bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that makes up this surface, he said, is loaded in bitumen.
When driving and exerting effort, this helps the forces to be very well spread over the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, said a chemical engineer.
On a sheet of asphalt, he added, was placed in the last layer, called the worn-out layer, which is made of a small stone, actually a sand that is also immersed in asphalt.
Since this is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it should be more resistant than asphalt coating and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and disseminate these efforts, wear and tear also requires proper thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature swings, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it had a significant impact on asphalt.
When the soil is raw, the water enters the surface and is difficult to escape from it, causing all layers of coating to soften and thus create a hole.
When creating a pit, he said, the first one was worn out and only then affected the bitumen, but the damage did not happen overnight, which should be taken into account in the first signs of ongoing maintenance programmes.
Also, a member of the National Research System explained that transport loads are another important factor in the formation of holes and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating must always be related to the transport load and this requirement must be guaranteed in order to prevent frequent pits.
Rafael Herrera said that much still needed to be studied and done about bitumen, such as bitumen emulsions, which in other countries were already on the market and even helped to make holes easily and without the use of high temperatures.
